@startuml
!include ../style.puml

title Serializable Layer Prevents Write Skew

' [step1 {"name":"Two snapshot transactions read the same invariant"}]
participant "Txn 1" as t1
participant "Txn 2" as t2
participant "Serializable replica" as replica

t1 -> replica: read doctor-alice = on-call
t1 -> replica: read doctor-bob = on-call
t2 -> replica: read doctor-alice = on-call
t2 -> replica: read doctor-bob = on-call

note over t1, t2
Invariant: at least one doctor must stay on-call.
Under snapshot isolation both txns think it is safe to turn one doctor off.
end note
' [/step1]

' [step2 {"name":"Module 06 tracks read provisional records"}]
replica -> replica: record that txn 1 read doctor-alice and doctor-bob
replica -> replica: record that txn 2 read doctor-alice and doctor-bob
' [/step2]

' [step3 {"name":"First write succeeds"}]
t1 -> replica: write doctor-alice = off-call
replica --> t1: success
' [/step3]

' [step4 {"name":"Second write conflicts", "newPage":"true"}]
t2 -> replica: write doctor-bob = off-call
replica -> replica: detect conflicting pending read\nfrom txn 1
replica --> t2: failure: Conflicting serializable read

note right of replica
Module 06 stops the skew before both txns commit.
That is a different problem from clock uncertainty:
the snapshot is safe, but the cross-key invariant is not.
end note
' [/step4]

' [step5 {"name":"Result preserves the invariant"}]
t1 -> replica: commit
replica --> t1: success

note over t1, t2
Final result:
doctor-alice = off-call
doctor-bob   = on-call
The invariant survives because one transaction was blocked.
end note
' [/step5]

@enduml
